      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20

I don=E2=80=99t know if you noticed, but I have spent   much of the   last =
six   months writing   about how Elon Musk, the world=E2=80=99s richest per=
son, doesn=E2=80=99t really care about his contractual obligations. Musk si=
gned a binding merger agreement to buy Twitter Inc. for $54.20 per share, a=
nd then decided he didn=E2=80=99t want to do that anymore, so he sent Twitt=
er a letter saying that the deal was off. Twitter said, no, we have a contr=
act, you can=E2=80=99t just change your mind. Twitter sued, and Musk fought=
 bitterly in court for a while. But Twitter was entirely right and he was e=
ntirely wrong: They had a binding contract, he had no good arguments for ge=
tting out of it, and courts=C2=A0tend to think that contracts matter even i=
f Elon Musk does not. Eventually he gave up: He didn=E2=80=99t lose in cour=
t, and he didn=E2=80=99t settle for some compromise; he just abandoned the =
fight and bought Twitter for $54.20 per share, as he had originally agreed.=
 The deal  closed last Thursday.
And then Elon Musk showed up for his first day of work as Twitter=E2=80=99s=
 chief executive officer =E2=80=94=C2=A0technically its   Chief Twit =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0and said =E2=80=9Chey, do you have any other contracts I could vio=
late?=E2=80=9D The  New York Times reports:

Late Thursday, he fired Twitter=E2=80=99s chief executive, chief financial =
officer and other executives. =E2=80=A6
Mr. Musk also appears unlikely to pay the golden parachutes that the fired =
top executives of Twitter were set to receive. Under the merger agreement, =
those executives =E2=80=94 including Parag Agrawal, the chief executive =E2=
=80=94 had been set to receive compensation of $20 million to $60 million i=
f they were fired. But Mr. Musk terminated the executives =E2=80=9Cfor caus=
e,=E2=80=9D meaning he did it because he alleged he had justification, whic=
h may void that agreement, two people with knowledge of the matter said.
Those executives, who also include the former chief financial officer Ned S=
egal, the former general counsel Sean Edgett, and the former top policy and=
 legal executive Vijaya Gadde, are deliberating their next steps, one perso=
n said.

The=C2=A0Financial Times adds:
In this instance, Musk=E2=80=99s argument is that Twitter has been mismanag=
ed and that if it were not for his bid, the value of the company=E2=80=99s =
stock would have collapsed, one of the people said. The executives, accordi=
ng to a person familiar with their thinking, are weighing their legal optio=
ns over the decision. Denying severance payments related to acquisitions is=
 unusual and the =E2=80=9Cfor cause=E2=80=9D clause typically requires misc=
onduct to have taken place.
I want to make a couple of points here. One is, I cannot believe we=E2=80=
=99re doing this again.
Another point is that he absolutely did not fire them for cause, as you can=
 easily tell by reading their employment agreements.
  [1]
=C2=A0Here is  the definition of =E2=80=9Ccause=E2=80=9D:
=E2=80=9CCause=E2=80=9D means (a) the unauthorized use or disclosure of Twi=
tter=E2=80=99s confidential information or trade secrets, which use or disc=
losure causes material harm to the Company; (b) the breach of any agreement=
 between the employee and Twitter; (c) the failure to comply with the Compa=
ny=E2=80=99s written policies or rules, including its code of conduct; (d) =
the conviction of, or plea of =E2=80=9Cguilty=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cno conte=
st=E2=80=9D to, a felony under the laws of the United States or any state t=
hereof; (e) gross negligence or willful misconduct in the performance of th=
e employee=E2=80=99s duties; (f) the continuing failure to perform assigned=
 duties after receiving written notification of the failure from the board =
of directors (or for Eligible Employees other than the Chief Executive Offi=
cer, from the Chief Executive Officer); or (g) the failure to cooperate in =
good faith with a governmental or internal investigation of Twitter or its =
directors, officers or employees, if Twitter has requested cooperation; pro=
vided, however, that =E2=80=9CCause=E2=80=9D will not be deemed to exist in=
 the event of subsections (b), (c) or (f) above unless the employee has bee=
n provided with (i) 30 days=E2=80=99 written notice by the Board or the act=
 or omission constituting =E2=80=9CCause=E2=80=9D and (ii) 30 days=E2=80=99=
 opportunity to cure such act or omission, if capable of cure.
I am not going to spend a lot of time=C2=A0parsing=C2=A0through that langua=
ge here, because Elon Musk doesn=E2=80=99t care, as we know from past exper=
ience. But did the fired Twitter executives do any of those things? Obvious=
ly not. Does Musk have any arguments that they did? Obviously not. Is he ev=
en pretending to have any relevant=C2=A0arguments? Obviously not. (=E2=80=
=9CThe value of the company=E2=80=99s stock would have collapsed=E2=80=9D: =
not on the list.) Will his lawyers try to clean up the mess by pretending t=
hat he had cause to fire the executives,=C2=A0saying that they allowed too =
many spam bots and that=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cgross negligence=E2=80=9D or wha=
tever? Obviously. Will he eventually have to pay them their full severance?=
 Obviously.=C2=A0Is this exactly in every respect like his decision to igno=
re the merger agreement? Pretty much, except that Musk essentially ended up=
 having to pay Twitter=E2=80=99s legal bills for that,
  [2]
=C2=A0but these executives will have to pay their own lawyers to go after M=
usk for this money. (Also Twitter could sue him in Delaware court, while th=
e executives will have to bring their claims to arbitration.)=C2=A0Very ann=
oying!
But I also want to make a broader point about why=C2=A0golden parachutes ex=
ist. Parag Agrawal has an employment agreement that says he gets a huge bag=
 of money if (1) Twitter is acquired and (2) then he is fired.
  [3]
=C2=A0He has been CEO for less than a year and stands to make tens of milli=
ons of dollars. Why did Twitter=E2=80=99s board agree to this deal? Why doe=
s almost every public company agree to that deal?
The answer is that sometimes public companies would be better off getting a=
cquired, but that would rarely make their=C2=A0CEOs=C2=A0better off, unless=
 they got paid. Earlier this year, Parag Agrawal had a good job as CEO of T=
witter. He got paid well, he got to boss people around, it was nice. Then E=
lon Musk came along and said, more or less in so many words, =E2=80=9CI wan=
t to buy Twitter and fire the CEO as rudely as possible.=E2=80=9D Agrawal m=
ight quite reasonably have said, no, I like my job, I like getting paid, I =
like being the boss, I don=E2=80=99t like people being rude and firing me. =
And then, as the CEO of Twitter, he could have tried to prevent the merger.=
 It might not have worked: Musk could have (and almost did) put in a hostil=
e bid to try to buy Twitter without the CEO=E2=80=99s approval; hostile bid=
s do sometimes succeed. But in general if a CEO wants to block a deal, that=
 makes it harder to do the deal.
But the deal was clearly (especially in hindsight) really good for Twitter=
=E2=80=99s shareholders: They got $54.20 per share, which is way more than =
the shares would otherwise be worth. And Twitter=E2=80=99s board had set up=
 incentives so that, if a deal came along that was good for shareholders bu=
t bad for Agrawal, Agrawal would say yes. The incentive is that Agrawal wou=
ld get fired rudely, but he=E2=80=99d get a big check to make up for it. I =
once   wrote about the general theory:
CEOs tend to receive=C2=A0whomping great =E2=80=9Cgolden parachutes=E2=80=
=9D for selling their companies, even if they=E2=80=99ve only been there a =
short time and haven=E2=80=99t done a very good job. Every time this happen=
s, people complain about it, but you shouldn=E2=80=99t think of the golden =
parachute as a reward for=C2=A0being the CEO. It=E2=80=99s an incentive to=
=C2=A0stop being the CEO:=C2=A0If the CEO=C2=A0knows he=E2=80=99ll get paid=
 $100 million for quitting in a merger, that might overcome his natural ave=
rsion to doing the merger.
Here, the golden parachutes worked=C2=A0perfectly. Agrawal and his manageme=
nt team clearly did not like Musk or want him to buy the company, and they =
clearly knew he would fire them,=C2=A0but they negotiated a deal with him a=
nyway,=C2=A0because it was in the best interests of shareholders. They put =
shareholder value above their own careers and interests, perhaps because th=
ey are noble people who love shareholder value, but perhaps also because th=
ey stood to get huge bags of money as a reward for this sacrifice.
And then he tried to get out of the deal! Elon Musk, a semi-hostile acquire=
r who clearly had it in for Agrawal et al., was like =E2=80=9Cokay never mi=
nd, not gonna buy Twitter.=E2=80=9D They could have let him walk! They coul=
d have said =E2=80=9Cokay he doesn=E2=80=99t want to buy Twitter and we don=
=E2=80=99t want to work for=C2=A0him briefly before he fires=C2=A0us, so th=
is worked out great for us, bye Elon.=E2=80=9D But instead they sued to for=
ce him to close the deal, and dealt with a lot of stress and online abuse, =
even though Musk didn=E2=80=99t want to buy Twitter and they didn=E2=80=99t=
 want him to buy Twitter. But they got it done anyway, because their=C2=A0s=
hareholders=C2=A0wanted Musk to buy Twitter, and they were working on behal=
f of the shareholders. And because they were incentivized, by their severan=
ce payments, to do that.
Let=E2=80=99s say Musk is entirely right that =E2=80=9CTwitter has been mis=
managed and that if it were not for his bid, the value of the company=E2=80=
=99s stock would have collapsed.=E2=80=9D That is why the golden parachutes=
 are there! If Twitter was managed great and worth more than his bid, he wo=
uldn=E2=80=99t have bought it, and they wouldn=E2=80=99t need severance! An=
d anyone can mismanage a company and drive down the stock price and then=C2=
=A0not=C2=A0sell the company to keep drawing a salary. Agrawal et al., let=
=E2=80=99s assume, mismanaged Twitter and drove down the stock price, but b=
ecause they were good stewards of shareholder value, they nonetheless manag=
ed to get a ton of money for shareholders. They have to be rewarded for tha=
t!
The basic problem with Musk=E2=80=99s efforts to walk away from his deal to=
 buy Twitter =E2=80=94=C2=A0beyond the transparent nonsense of his actual a=
rguments =E2=80=94=C2=A0was that if he could walk away from this deal then=
=C2=A0no=C2=A0merger agreement would be binding; every buyer could change t=
heir mind and go to court and say =E2=80=9Cmeh, contracts, they don=E2=80=
=99t matter.=E2=80=9D That did not work out for him; the system held.
The basic problem with Musk=E2=80=99s efforts to walk away from these sever=
ance agreements =E2=80=94=C2=A0beyond the lack of actual arguments =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0is that if he can stiff these executives then=C2=A0no golden parac=
hute is binding. The point of a golden parachute is that a CEO with a golde=
n parachute will sell his company to a buyer whom he doesn=E2=80=99t like, =
if that=E2=80=99s what is best for shareholders. If the buyer can stiff the=
 CEO on the parachute payments because they don=E2=80=99t like each other, =
then no buyer will ever pay severance, and no CEO will ever trust it.

