 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;">Financial Times adds</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In this instance, Musk=E2=80=99s a=
rgument is that Twitter has been mismanaged and that if it were not for his=
 bid, the value of the company=E2=80=99s stock would have collapsed, one of=
 the people said. The executives, according to a person familiar with their=
 thinking, are weighing their legal options over the decision. Denying seve=
rance payments related to acquisitions is unusual and the =E2=80=9Cfor caus=
e=E2=80=9D clause typically requires misconduct to have taken place.</p></b=
lockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I want to make a couple of points here. One is=
, I cannot believe we=E2=80=99re doing this again.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another point is that he absolutely did not fi=
re them for cause, as you can easily tell by reading their employment agree=
ments.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000=
000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bot=
tom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color:=
 transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
29546575.290502/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MTg=
wOTEvMDAwMTU2NDU5MDE1MDAyNjgyL3R3dHItZGVmMTRhXzIwMTUwNjAzLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cB86ebd4b7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the definition of =E2=80=9Ccause=E2=80=9D<=
/a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CCause=E2=80=9D means (a) =
the unauthorized use or disclosure of Twitter=E2=80=99s confidential inform=
ation or trade secrets, which use or disclosure causes material harm to the=
 Company; (b) the breach of any agreement between the employee and Twitter;=
 (c) the failure to comply with the Company=E2=80=99s written policies or r=
ules, including its code of conduct; (d) the conviction of, or plea of =E2=
=80=9Cguilty=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cno contest=E2=80=9D to, a felony under th=
e laws of the United States or any state thereof; (e) gross negligence or w=
illful misconduct in the performance of the employee=E2=80=99s duties; (f) =
the continuing failure to perform assigned duties after receiving written n=
otification of the failure from the board of directors (or for Eligible Emp=
loyees other than the Chief Executive Officer, from the Chief Executive Off=
icer); or (g) the failure to cooperate in good faith with a governmental or=
 internal investigation of Twitter or its directors, officers or employees,=
 if Twitter has requested cooperation; provided, however, that =E2=80=9CCau=
se=E2=80=9D will not be deemed to exist in the event of subsections (b), (c=
) or (f) above unless the employee has been provided with (i) 30 days=E2=80=
=99 written notice by the Board or the act or omission constituting =E2=80=
=9CCause=E2=80=9D and (ii) 30 days=E2=80=99 opportunity to cure such act or=
 omission, if capable of cure.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am not going to spend a lot of time=C2=A0par=
sing=C2=A0through that language here, because Elon Musk doesn=E2=80=99t car=
e, as we know from past experience. But did the fired Twitter executives do=
 any of those things? Obviously not. Does Musk have any arguments that they=
 did? Obviously not. Is he even pretending to have any relevant=C2=A0argume=
nts? Obviously not. (=E2=80=9CThe value of the company=E2=80=99s stock woul=
d have collapsed=E2=80=9D: not on the list.) Will his lawyers try to clean =
up the mess by pretending that he had cause to fire the executives,=C2=A0sa=
ying that they allowed too many spam bots and that=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cgross=
 negligence=E2=80=9D or whatever? Obviously. Will he eventually have to pay=
 them their full severance? Obviously.=C2=A0Is this exactly in every respec=
t like his decision to ignore the merger agreement? Pretty much, except tha=
t Musk essentially ended up having to pay Twitter=E2=80=99s legal bills for=
 that,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000=
000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bot=
tom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color:=
 transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0but these executives will have to pay their own lawyers to go aft=
er Musk for this money. (Also Twitter could sue him in Delaware court, whil=
e the executives will have to bring their claims to arbitration.)=C2=A0Very=
 annoying!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But I also want to make a broader point about =
why=C2=A0golden parachutes exist. Parag Agrawal has an employment agreement=
 that says he gets a huge bag of money if (1) Twitter is acquired and (2) t=
hen he is fired.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgro=
und-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0He has been CEO for less than a year and stands to make tens of m=
illions of dollars. Why did Twitter=E2=80=99s board agree to this deal? Why=
 does almost every public company agree to that deal?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The answer is that sometimes public companies =
would be better off getting acquired, but that would rarely make their=C2=
=A0<em>CEOs=C2=A0</em>better off, unless they got paid. Earlier this year, =
Parag Agrawal had a good job as CEO of Twitter. He got paid well, he got to=
 boss people around, it was nice. Then Elon Musk came along and said, more =
or less in so many words, =E2=80=9CI want to buy Twitter and fire the CEO a=
s rudely as possible.=E2=80=9D Agrawal might quite reasonably have said, no=
, I like my job, I like getting paid, I like being the boss, I don=E2=80=99=
t like people being rude and firing me. And then, as the CEO of Twitter, he=
 could have tried to prevent the merger. It might not have worked: Musk cou=
ld have (and almost did) put in a hostile bid to try to buy Twitter without=
 the CEO=E2=80=99s approval; hostile bids do sometimes succeed. But in gene=
ral if a CEO wants to block a deal, that makes it harder to do the deal.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the deal was clearly (especially in hindsi=
ght) really good for Twitter=E2=80=99s shareholders: They got $54.20 per sh=
are, which is way more than the shares would otherwise be worth. And Twitte=
r=E2=80=99s board had set up incentives so that, if a deal came along that =
was good for shareholders but bad for Agrawal, Agrawal would say yes. The i=
ncentive is that Agrawal would get fired rudely, but he=E2=80=99d get a big=
 check to make up for it. I once <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/29546575.290502/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9u=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMTAtMzEvd2hlbi1jZW9zLWNhbGwtdGhlaXItY29tcGFuaWVzLXVnbHk=
_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTAzMTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW=
5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMDMxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB445eb983" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  wrote about the general theory</a>:</p=
>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">CEOs tend to receive=C2=A0whomping=
 great =E2=80=9Cgolden parachutes=E2=80=9D for selling their companies, eve=
n if they=E2=80=99ve only been there a short time and haven=E2=80=99t done =
a very good job. Every time this happens, people complain about it, but you=
 shouldn=E2=80=99t think of the golden parachute as a reward for=C2=A0<em>b=
eing the CEO</em>. It=E2=80=99s an incentive to=C2=A0<em>stop being the CEO=
:=C2=A0</em>If the CEO=C2=A0knows he=E2=80=99ll get paid $100 million for q=
uitting in a merger, that might overcome his natural aversion to doing the =
merger.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here, the golden parachutes worked=C2=A0<em>pe=
rfectly</em>. Agrawal and his management team clearly did not like Musk or =
want him to buy the company, and they clearly knew he would fire them,=C2=
=A0but they negotiated a deal with him anyway,=C2=A0<em>because it was in t=
he best interests of shareholders</em>. They put shareholder value above th=
eir own careers and interests, perhaps because they are noble people who lo=
ve shareholder value, but perhaps also because they stood to get huge bags =
of money as a reward for this sacrifice.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then he tried to get out of the deal! Elon=
 Musk, a semi-hostile acquirer who clearly had it in for Agrawal et al., wa=
s like =E2=80=9Cokay never mind, not gonna buy Twitter.=E2=80=9D They could=
 have let him walk! They could have said =E2=80=9Cokay he doesn=E2=80=99t w=
ant to buy Twitter and we don=E2=80=99t want to work for=C2=A0him briefly b=
efore he fires=C2=A0us, so this worked out great for us, bye Elon.=E2=80=9D=
 But instead they sued to force him to close the deal, and dealt with a lot=
 of stress and online abuse, even though Musk didn=E2=80=99t want to buy Tw=
itter and they didn=E2=80=99t want him to buy Twitter. But they got it done=
 anyway, because their=C2=A0<em>shareholders=C2=A0</em>wanted Musk to buy T=
witter, and they were working on behalf of the shareholders. And because th=
ey were incentivized, by their severance payments, to do that.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Let=E2=80=99s say Musk is entirely right that =
=E2=80=9CTwitter has been mismanaged and that if it were not for his bid, t=
he value of the company=E2=80=99s stock would have collapsed.=E2=80=9D That=
 is <em>why the golden parachutes are there</em>! If Twitter was managed gr=
eat and worth more than his bid, he wouldn=E2=80=99t have bought it, and th=
ey wouldn=E2=80=99t need severance! And anyone can mismanage a company and =
drive down the stock price and then=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>sell the company=
 to keep drawing a salary. Agrawal et al., let=E2=80=99s assume, mismanaged=
 Twitter and drove down the stock price, but because they were good steward=
s of shareholder value, they nonetheless managed to get a ton of money for =
shareholders. They have to be rewarded for that!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic problem with Musk=E2=80=99s efforts =
to walk away from his deal to buy Twitter =E2=80=94=C2=A0beyond the transpa=
rent nonsense of his actual arguments =E2=80=94=C2=A0was that if he could w=
alk away from this deal then=C2=A0<em>no=C2=A0</em>merger agreement would b=
e binding; every buyer could change their mind and go to court and say =E2=
=80=9Cmeh, contracts, they don=E2=80=99t matter.=E2=80=9D That did not work=
 out for him; the system held.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic problem with Musk=E2=80=99s efforts =
to walk away from these severance agreements =E2=80=94=C2=A0beyond the lack=
 of actual arguments =E2=80=94=C2=A0is that if he can stiff these executive=
s then=C2=A0<em>no</em> golden parachute is binding. The point of a golden =
parachute is that a CEO with a golden parachute will sell his company to a =
buyer whom he doesn=E2=80=99t like, if that=E2=80=99s what is best for shar=
eholders. If the buyer can stiff the CEO on the parachute payments because =
they don=E2=80=99t like each other, then no buyer will ever pay severance, =
and no CEO will ever trust it.</p>
