oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> he wrote</a>, =
in a famous letter to shareholders in the initial public offering. =E2=80=
=9CIt was built to accomplish a social mission =E2=80=94 to make the world =
more open and connected.=E2=80=9D The subtext of this letter =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0and of Zuckerberg retaining control of the company with his high-voting =
shares of stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0was =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t bother me about m=
aking money, I=E2=80=99m just going to make Facebook run the way I want it =
to, and maybe in the long run that will work out but it=E2=80=99s not my pr=
oblem.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">People who bought =
stock in the IPO were taking a big risk, giving money to Zuckerberg to use =
as he saw fit, without much promise that he=E2=80=99d make them any money.<=
/li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Then Zuckerberg made absolute ocea=
ns of money for those investors, amply justifying their trust.</li>=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Then Zuckerberg was like =E2=80=9Cyou know wha=
t, never mind, forget this Facebook stuff, we=E2=80=99re gonna do a metaver=
se.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The investors were li=
ke =E2=80=9Cwait a minute this is a terrible idea.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li styl=
e=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Zuckerberg glared at them and tapped the sharehol=
der letter again.</li>
